<bill id="DLM2061900" in.amend="false" irdnumbering="no" official="yes" xml:lang="en-NZ" year.imprint="2009" bill.no="39" bill.type="government" stage="2" year="2009">
  <billdetail>
    <title>Motor Vehicle Sales Amendment Bill</title>
    <billtype>Government Bill</billtype>
    <repnote>As reported from the Commerce Committee</repnote>
    <commentary id="DLM2641000" in.amend="false" irdnumbering="no" official="yes" bill.no="39" bill.type="government" stage="2" year="2009">
      <heading>Commentary</heading>
      <comm.lev1>
        <heading>Recommendation</heading>
        <para>
          <text>The Commerce Committee has examined the Motor Vehicle Sales Amendment Bill and recommends that it be passed with the amendments shown.</text>
        </para>
      </comm.lev1>
      <comm.lev1>
        <heading>Introduction</heading>
        <para>
          <text>This bill would amend the Motor Vehicle Sales Act 2003 to improve its operation.</text>
        </para>
        <para>
          <text>Minor, technical, and consequential amendments are not covered in this commentary.</text>
        </para>
      </comm.lev1>
      <comm.lev1>
        <heading>Display of a consumer information notice</heading>
        <para>
          <text>We recommend that clause 7 be amended to make it clear that the Motor Vehicle Sales Act requires motor vehicle traders to display a consumer information notice when displaying or offering for sale a used motor vehicle physically, or when displaying or offering for sale a used motor vehicle over the internet when a contract to buy the motor vehicle can be entered into on line.</text>
        </para>
        <para>
          <text>This is to distinguish between internet advertisements that offer the ability to enter into a contract to buy the vehicle on line, and therefore should display a consumer information notice, and advertisements that are effectively classified advertisements, for which the provision of a consumer information notice would be an unnecessary and onerous requirement.</text>
        </para>
      </comm.lev1>
      <comm.lev1>
        <heading>Statutory declaration for new overseas directors</heading>
        <para>
          <text>We recommend that clause 12, inserting new section 40A into the Act, be amended by inserting new subsections (4) and (5). New section 40A would impose an obligation on motor vehicle traders that are companies to notify the Registrar if a new person became involved in the management of the company. This would ensure that the information about the management personnel of a registered motor vehicle trader was kept up to date between registration renewals.</text>
        </para>
        <para>
          <text>We heard arguments that this would place unreasonable administration and compliance costs on overseas companies, such as the major Japanese car manufacturers, who would have to arrange for their new directors to sign a statutory declaration and file it with the Registrar. </text>
        </para>
        <para>
          <text>As this was not the intention of new section 40A, we recommend an amendment to make the requirements less onerous for them, by allowing new overseas directors to self-certify that they are not disqualified from registration in their own right. No more than three directors would be able to rely on self-certification at any time.</text>
        </para>
      </comm.lev1>
      <comm.lev1>
        <heading>Jurisdiction of the Motor Vehicle Disputes Tribunal</heading>
        <para>
          <text>We recommend the insertion of new clause 15A, which would give the Motor Vehicle Disputes Tribunal the ability to hear claims under the Contractual Remedies Act 1979, as well as other Acts currently provided for. </text>
        </para>
      </comm.lev1>
      <comm.appendix>
        <heading>Appendix</heading>
        <comm.lev2>
          <heading>Committee process</heading>
          <para>
            <text>The Motor Vehicle Sales Amendment Bill was referred to the committee on 30 June 2009. The closing date for submissions was 20 August 2009. We received and considered eight submissions from interested groups and individuals. We heard two submissions.</text>
          </para>
          <para>
            <text>We received advice from the Ministry of Consumer Affairs. </text>
          </para>
        </comm.lev2>
        <comm.lev2>
          <heading>Committee membership</heading>
          <para>
            <text>Hon Lianne Dalziel (Chairperson)</text>
          </para>
          <para>
            <text>John Boscawen</text>
          </para>
